instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is architected around three core layers: data acquisition, modelling, and control/optimization algorithms. Sensors on the physical twin emit raw telemetry that is streamed in real‑time (latency typically in the order of milliseconds) into the DT’s data layer, where it is stored in a time‑series database. Calibration algorithms continuously ingest this data to refine the parameters of both cyber (software) and physical (mechanical, environmental) models, ensuring that model predictions remain aligned with actual measurements. A monitoring service consumes the updated predictions and real‑time data to evaluate safety and performance metrics; any detected violations trigger either automated corrective actions or human operators via a decision‑support interface. The system employs a publish/subscribe messaging pattern (e.g., MQTT or RabbitMQ) to coordinate between components, enabling low‑latency communication between the calibration, monitoring, and optimization layers. Resource management is handled through container orchestration (e.g., Docker Compose or Kubernetes), allocating CPU, memory, and network bandwidth to each service based on demand and QoS requirements. This layered orchestration pattern allows tight coupling between physical behavior and digital reaction, while preserving scalability and modularity."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Calibration algorithms update the models of the CPS and environment with the best estimate of parameters, and the resulting data is used by monitors to verify whether the system is performing safely and optimally. Detailed validation and verification methods, uncertainty quantification, error‑correction mechanisms, and quality assurance processes are not specified in the document."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The DT framework incorporates runtime safety monitoring by continuously evaluating the system's operating parameters against predefined safety and performance thresholds. The monitored sensor outputs are fed into safety monitors which, upon detecting a violation, can trigger a safe‑mode response or halt system operation to prevent hazards. These safety checks are integral to the calibration workflow that updates models based on real‑time data, ensuring that any deviations from expected behavior are identified and addressed before they propagate to the physical twin. No explicit cybersecurity or access‑control mechanisms are described in the provided material."
]
